# Part 4 – Institutional Applications

The Trust Framework is intentionally abstract.  

Institutional applications provide worked examples showing how its layers operate within specific cooperative systems.

This section introduces a stylised marine insurance market used to illustrate the framework in practice. 

The objective is not to optimise a particular insurance product, but to examine how combinations of underwriting discipline, capital management, and renewal behaviour perform over time within a shared trust environment.

## Application A – Marine Insurance Trust Market Simulation (SIM F)

This section presents a case study of the Trust Framework applied to a multi-agent marine insurance market.

The **SIM F** model implements the interaction of contribution, trust formation, credibility formation, credit allocation, coordination behaviour, coexistent institutional systems, and continuation outcomes within a single simulation environment.

The simulation therefore provides a concrete institutional setting in which the abstract layers of the Trust Framework can be illustrated dynamically.

In particular, the simulation highlights how institutional doctrines influence operational capacity over time through their impact on trust, credibility, and capital allocation.

## Role of SIM F in the Trust Framework

SIM F is a self-contained simulation of a stylised marine insurance market in which multiple agents write shared risks over repeated periods.

The simulation is not part of the core Trust Framework. Instead, it serves as a worked institutional example illustrating how the framework’s abstract layers can operate within a concrete cooperative system.

In particular, SIM F demonstrates how the following layers interact dynamically:
- contribution,
- trust formation,
- credibility formation,
- credit formation,
- temporal coordination,
- coordination boundary,
- coexistent systems, and
- continuation,

The purpose of the simulation is therefore illustrative rather than foundational. 

All definitions and principles of the Trust Framework remain valid independently of any specific simulation environment.

### Mapping of Trust Framework layers into SIM F (informal)

The table below illustrates how the conceptual layers of the Trust Framework are represented within the SIM F simulation environment.


| Trust layer             | SIM F illustration (marine market)                            |
|-------------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------|
| Contribution            | Premium − loss delivered per period (per agent, per voyage)   |
| Trust formation         | Owner and market renewal decisions, ORR paths                 |
| Credibility formation   | Stable line share and market allocation over time             |
| Credit formation        | Capital and RC committed to shared risks                      |
| Temporal coordination   | Multi‑period evolution of capital, float, and renewal cycles  |
| Coordination boundary   | Line allocation rules, prudential and investor constraints    |
| Coexistent systems      | Multiple doctrines coexisting on the same voyages             |
| Continuation            | Solvent active vs runoff vs trust collapse vs insolvency      |

The Trust Framework itself does not depend on any specific simulation. SIM F is deliberately presented as a separate, optional case study. 

All definitions and principles introduced in earlier parts remain valid whether or not a particular application like SIM F is used. 

The role of SIM F is therefore illustrative rather than foundational. It provides a controlled institutional setting in which the abstract mechanisms of contribution, trust formation, credibility formation, credit allocation, and continuation can be observed dynamically.

Although the present application uses a marine insurance market, the same structural pattern can be translated to other institutional contexts such as interbank funding markets, clearing systems, or platform ecosystems without relying on marine-specific assumptions.

Although this application uses a marine insurance market, the structure of SIM F is deliberately generic:

At an abstract level, the simulation contains:
- agents with doctrines and capital,
- shared exposures,
- bilateral trust and renewal decisions, and
- multiple institutional failure nodes.

These elements represent a general cooperative system rather than marine-specific assumptions.

The same structural pattern can therefore be translated into other institutional environments, such as interbank funding networks, clearing membership systems, or platform ecosystems).

In this sense, SIM F provides a reusable blueprint for **capacity-lens institutional applications** of the Trust Framework.

